Population B formed the largest and tightest cluster and three toms and four queens were selected from among this group to create a parental (P) generation. These seven cats produced 57 F1 kittens between them (Table 1
). One F1 female (12-4A) was bred once with her father (11-166) and once with a full brother of the father (11-225) to produced six F1/P-backcross kittens (Table 1). The breeding program was terminated at this point based on the results of subsequent FIPV challenge-exposures. Table 2
provides a genetic assessment of the P, F1 and F1/P backcross populations based on a panel of 42 STR loci. The average alleles/locus (Aa) and the average effective alleles/locus (Ae) remained the same in the P and F1 cats, but decreased in the F1/P backcrosses. Observed heterozygosity (Ho) decreased from the P to F1/P generations, reflecting the inbreeding. An increase in genome-wide homozygosity based on alleles at each of 42 genome-wide STR loci was also observed between the P and F1/P backcross generations (Table 3
).
